---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="About · America's School Trust Library"
      description="America's School Trust Library is the evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands and funds. A project of Advocates for School Trust Lands (ASTL), a national 501(c)(3) nonprofit."
    />
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-archive-paper text-ink" data-source-id="about-page">
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-prose p-4 sm:p-8">
      <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
        <h1>About America's School Trust Library</h1>

        <h2>Mission</h2>
        <p>
          America's School Trust Library is the evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands and funds. It exists to make the legal architecture, financial scale, and political accountability of these trusts visible — to journalists, lawyers, legislators, trustees, and citizens.
        </p>

        <h2>A project of ASTL</h2>
        <p>
          The Library is a project of <strong>Advocates for School Trust Lands (ASTL)</strong>, a national 501(c)(3) nonprofit advancing fiduciary integrity in America's school trust lands and funds. ASTL is the parent organization. The Library is its public-facing research resource and public ledger.
        </p>
        <p>
          ASTL also has a state-level affiliate in Oregon — <strong>Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands (OASTL)</strong> — which is the active plaintiff in Oregon's current trust-breach litigation. OASTL's organizational page lives at <a href="https://oastl.org">oastl.org</a>; OASTL-specific case material lives in this Library at <a href="/oastl/">/oastl/</a> (in development).
        </p>

        <h2>Substrate and method</h2>
        <p>
          The library is built on a five-layer Knowledge Stack: primary sources (statutes, court opinions, treaties, historical maps, expert declarations); canonical claims (atomized facts and arguments, every one cited to source); audience models (different readers need different pieces); a toolchain of human and AI editors; and the deliverables you see on these pages. The substrate is documented and version-controlled; the build pipeline is reproducible.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every figure on this site carries a confidence badge. Every blank cell is a signal — most often that a state has not disclosed the underlying data. Visible incompleteness is the path to credibility for a public ledger of public trusts.
        </p>

        <h2>Team</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Dave Sullivan — CEO, retired professor, lead OASTL plaintiff in Oregon's trust-breach litigation.</li>
          <li>Margaret Bird — co-author, national domain authority on school trust lands.</li>
          <li>Daniel Zene Crowe — OASTL General Counsel, lead on the 2024 Oregon case.</li>
          <li>Natalie Scott — lead on the 2023 Oregon case (January 2026 Court of Appeals standing victory).</li>
          <li>Laura — legal research bridge.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Contact and corrections</h2>
        <p>
          For corrections, source additions, or story tips: <a href="https://github.com/dave-schooltrustlands/schooltrustlands-encyclopedia/issues">GitHub issues</a> or email contact via the parent organization at <a href="https://schooltrustlands.org">schooltrustlands.org</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Citation guidance: see <a href="/about/cite/">/about/cite/</a>.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
